05154nam a22008295i 9780231529709DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2010    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315297097 a10.7312/luis145502doi  a(DE-B1597)459080  a(OCoLC)826476545  a(OCoLC)979577376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBQ4570 .M37 L85 2010 7aREL1060002bisacsh04a294.3/3657a294.336571 aLuisi, Pier, eauthor.10aMind and Life :bDiscussions with the Dalai Lama on the Nature of Reality /cPier Luisi. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource :b59 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Series in Science and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 / How Real Are the Elementary Particles? -- t2 / The Emergence of Complexity AND AN INTERVIEW WITH MATTHIEU RICARD -- t3 / Toward the Complexity of Life -- t4 / How Life Unfolds AND AN INTERVIEW WITH RICHARD GERE -- t5 / The Magic of the Human Genome and Its Ethical Problems AND AN INTERVIEW WITH HIS HOLINESS THE KARMAPA -- t6 / From Consciousness to Ethics -- t7 / Last Words -- tAbout the Mind and Life Institute / rEngle, R. Adam / Houshmand, Zara -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over a decade, a small group of scientists and philosophersmembers of the Mind and Life Institutehave met regularly to explore the intersection between science and the spirit. At one of these meetings, the themes discussed were both fundamental and profound: can physics, chemistry, and biology explain the mystery of life? How do our philosophical assumptions influence science and the ethics we bring to biotechnology? And how does an ancient spiritual tradition throw new light on these questions?Pier Luigi Luisi not only reproduces this dramatic, cross-cultural dialogue, in which world-class scientists, philosophers, and Buddhist scholars develop a holistic approach to the scientific exploration of reality, but also adds scientific background to their presentations, as well as supplementary discussions with prominent participants and attendees. Interviews with His Holiness the Karmapa, the Buddhist monk Matthieu Ricard, and the actor and longtime human rights advocate Richard Gere take the proceedings into new directions, enriching the material with personal viewpoints and lively conversation about such topics as the origin of matter, the properties of cells, the nature of evolution, the ethics of genetic manipulation, and the question of consciousness and ethics. A keen study of character, Luisi incorporates his own amusing observations into this fascinating dialogue, painting a very human portrait of some of our greatestand most intimidatingthinkers. Deeply textured and cleverly crafted, Mind and Life is an excellent opportunity for any reader to join in the debate surrounding this cutting-edge field of inquiry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBiologyxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aBuddhist philosophy. 0aLifexReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aMatterxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh1 aHoushmand, Zara.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/luis14550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231529709.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-1